{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_doyle_ver01/data/sn86091100/00415666172/1914022601/0842.xml":{"full_text":"IDAHO COUNTY FREE PRESS\n-_LEADING PAPER of IDAHO COUNTY. PRINTS ALL THE OFFICIAL PROCEEDINGS.\nroL. 28, NO. 40\nGRANGEVILLE, IDAHO, THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 26, 1914\n$2.00 PER YEAR.\nmail\nDIAN LAND TAX\nHATTERS TO IE\naEE COUNTIES JOIN HANDS TO\nASK APPROPRIATIONS FROM\nu. S. GOVERNMENT.\nAT LEWISTON TODAY\nrant Money From Department of In\ndian Affairs to Build Highways\nThrough Indian Lands.\n(Special Dispatch to Free Press.)\nLewiston, February 26.\nof Idaho, Clearwater and Lewis\nill ask the national department of\nidian affairs at Washington, D. C., for\njoint appropriation to build roads in\narious parts of the three counties, ac\n>rdiug to a decision reached here to\nay at a meeting attended by delegates\n\u00bbpointed from the counties concerned,\nhe meeting was held at the Lewiston\nommercial club, and tikis organization\ni taking a prominent part in the nego\nlatiou to secure the appropriations.\n'The united action of the three coun\nts comes as a result of the govern\nleut's poliey in adhering to the time\nroru practice of non-taxation of In\niau lauds. Where the Indians lands\nre not taxed, there is, of course, a lack\nf funds for road building and other\nublic improvements and the good\njails enthusiasts of the three counties\noted to join together in an urgent re\nuest upou the government asking for a\ntraight appropriation to offset the\nack of funds that might be derived\nrom taxation were that method of rais\nig money in vogue.\nRemoves Serious Obstruction.\nIt is thought that as a result of to\nay's action the counties will receive\nid from Washington and that in this\nray the obstruction of building good\noads in territory where Indian land is\n>eated will be overcome. The fact that\nio funds or taxes could be collected\nIndian land has seriously retarted\n)ad buildings in those sections of the\n\u00bbunties for years, it is claimed.\nIdaho county was represented in to\nay'8 meeting by John A. Powell, presi\nent of the Idaho County Good Roads\nassociation, and W. _. Hussman, of\nlottonwood, one of the county's most\nlarnest and active advocates of modern\nlighways.\nThe\ncoun\nles\nrom\nHELD DISTRICT MEETING.\nA mass meeting of the people resid\nn g in Mt. Idaho Highway district was\n'eld last Saturday at the Delaney\nschool house and proved such\n'hat those present voted to make it an\n'nnual affair. A large attendance was\n\u00bbresent and issues effecting the science\nroad building, as applied particular\ny to the highways within the bounda\n\u25a0es of the Mt. Idaho district, were dis\ncussed\na success\nfrankly,\n\u00abte was had\nConsiderable de\nupon the preference of\nbuilding wide or narrow roads und it\nAppeared that the advocates of building\ne narrower highways were in the ma\nSority. A vote of thanks for tho pre\ni* a t con 'missioners .expressing appro\nNion of their\npast efforts and -'u\nouraging them to continue the good\nr r k, was placed on record,\njissioners are James Surridge, William\n&nson and Gus Wickman. George\ntephens ia\nThe '\u2022''in\nsecretary of the boa.ii.\nHY THE MAIL WAS LATE.\ne P she's busted; lost the blamed\nking bolt,\" these and other expres\nse ami\nexplanatory remarks filled the\nv near the old Robbins place Sunday\n'ening when something went wrong\nthe Whitebird stage. Dave Brown,\n\"uffeu, laid down the\nr rlei1 un er the machine, expecting\n0 f '\u00bbd the\nreins and\nsteering gear out of kilter,\na the absence of the king bolt and\nP r esence of a few other minor diffi\nles to *d him only too well that the\nWou *d have to be abandoned and\nrestored to for the rest of the\n\u25a0\">\"rncy. 8o Dave\nproper\narranged for the\n''\"re of the mail and express\n'oith a mail sack\n\u00b0\"e of the horses and came in to\na ke\\ille, arriving late at night. The\nh\u00df went out to the scene\ne disaster and brought the disabl\n'raft to town where\nor two climbed\n\u00bbto\n\u00bbext\nrepairs were\nde.\nmail cashiers organize.\nThe rural route mail carriers working\nout from the local postoffice ami Car\nrier Harley Clark of Culdesac, in re -1\nsponce to the call of F. O. Paul, of Rex-\nburg, state president of the Rural Car\nriers of Idaho, met here Monday and\norganized a county association. The\nmeeting was called to order by H. J.\nMunro as temporary chairman and the\nelection of officers resulted as fol\nlows:\n\n\n1\nH. J. Munro president, Harley\nsecretary-treasurer, and J. W.\nHeath vice president. Resolutions\nadopted as follows:\nClark\nwere\n\"Resolved that\nthis association be known as the Lewis,\nNez Perce and Idaho County Rural Let\nter Carrier's Association; that the\ndues for each year be 25e per member;\nthat each carrier be requested to join\nthe county, state and national associa\ntion; that the salary of the rural\nriers should be increased to $1200\nyear for a standard route of 24 miles\nand $48 a year for/each additional mile\ncar\na\nor fraction thereof; that patrons of\nrural routes be required to erect parcel\npost boxes; that a maintenance fund\nshould be granted the rural carriers,\nsuch to be not less than $120 and not\nto exceed $300 per year; that a copy of\nthe minutes of this meeting be sent to\neach carrier in above counties with the\nrequest to join the association, also that\na copy be sent to our state president;\nthat our next meeting be held at Ho,\nthe 30th of May.\"\nCLUB HAS GOOD TIMES.\nCamas Social Club No. 1 had its last\nregular meeting with Mrs. Geo. Schleier.\nAfter business meeting a dainty lunch\nwas served and all present spent a very\npleasant afternoon. The next regular\nmeeting will be with Mrs. Butler. The\nclub gave a Hard Times Social at the\nStar school house last Friday evening\nfrom which a neat little sum was realiz\ned to swell the treasury of the club\nand Star school district. Prizes were\noffered to the lady and gentleman who\nwould dress to best personate hard\ntimes. Mrs. Schleier and Earl Battles\nwere the lucky contestants. The club\nalso gave Mr. and Mrs. S. M. Howard\na surprise party Saturday night it be\ning the occasion of their twentieth wed\nding anniversary. After supper games\nand conversation were indulged in until\na late hour. When all departed with\nmany expressions of having had a good\ntime and wishing Mr. and Mrs. Howard\nmany anniversary returns together in\nthis world. Before leaving they pre\nsented Mrs. Howard with some choice\npieces of china.\na\nIS PIONEER MERCHANT.\nL. Spengler, who is indeed one of the\npioneer merchants of Idaho county, was\nin the city the first of the week look\ning after business matters and shaking\nhands with\nhis many friends. Mr.\nSpengler' has been engaged in the mer\ncantile business on the prairie for the\npast 16 years, four years of which he\nspent at Denver where his store was\nheadquarters for the townspeople and\npractically the commercial center of\nthe town. From Denver he moved his\nstore to Tharp when the railroad in\nvaded the prairie country and for the\npast four years his place has been one\nof the leading trading points on the\nHe has recently disposed of\nprairie.\nhis store to Marion Webber, his son-in\nlaw who now has charge of the estab\nlishment and is constantly adding goods\nto the various lines. Mr. Spengler\nwishes to thank his past patrons for\ntheir liberal business and bespeaks the\nsame for his successor.\nST. PATRICK'S DAY BALL.\nThe Rebekahs announce a grand St.\nPatrick's ball to be given at the Sch\nmadeka hall on the evening of Tuesday,\nMarch 17. It was originally intended\nto hold a mask ball but the ladies have\ndecided to dispense with this feature.\nThe popular Orangeville orchestra will\nprovide music for the event and this\nfact together with the probable intro\nduction of unique and interesting novel\nties assures a very enjoyable evening\nfor all who attend. The ladies wish to\ncall special attention to the announce\nment that the masquerade feature has\nbeen dropped.\nHAVE FAREWELL PARTY.\nA number of friends of Mr. and Mrs.\nA. V. Overman surprised them ai their\nhome in this city last evening by walk\ning in unannounced and proceeding to\ntake full possession of the house until\nGames and amusements\nimmensely enjoyed and a bounti\nful supper served. Most all the guests\nmembers of the Methodist Sunday\na late hour.\nwere\nwere\nschool and the affair was in the nature\nof a farewell party in honor of Mr. and\nMrs. Overman, who intend to leave soon\nfor their new home in Spokane.\nA Mother of Bearded Men\na\n\n\n\nI am the. mother of bearded men, and the names that\nI called them by\nlien I watched their sleep in their cradles, and\nhushed each tear and sigh,\nAre known and spoken where men meet men, and\nlife moves swift along,\nFor they do their share of the world's work, and\nthey are sure and strong.\nClear are their eyes and their glances kind, as when\ntheir years were few;\nDeep voices call me mother, and the tones are gentle\nand true;\nThey give me love and honor, though they\nnow than I,\nBut 1 think of the little children who slept in my\narms and I sigh.\n1\nare wiser\nOil, I could not hold them dearer, and I would not\nturn them back\nTo wander again through life's thorny maze, and\nagain to climb the track,\nBut when the lonely evening comes, and no one has\nneed of me,\nIt's Oh, for the little children who once leaned upon\nmy knee!\n\u2014Niuetta M Lcwater.\nNEW MAGAZINE ISSUED.\nLocal sportsmen have received copies\nof the initial number of the new Idaho\nFish ami Game magazine, a peridocial\npublished mouthly at Boise by the state\ngame department under the guiding\nhand of State Game Warden Barber\nwho has had long experience in the\nnewspaper world. The first adition is\na splendid issue, well written and well\nprinted and the magazine bids fair to\nattain considerable popularity.\nFisher, local deputy, submits au inter\nesting report and, in addition to this,\nother Idaho county game and fish\nstories are given prominence. Speak\ning personally in the foreword Editor\nWarden Barber says in part: \"Idaho\nFish and Game is published as an auxi\nliary to the work of the fish and game\ndepartment, it will be a 'deputy with\nout pay,' working at all times for\nwhat its publisher believes to be for\nthe best interests of the department\nand of the people who support the de\npartment. It will not cost the depart\nment nor the taxpayers one cent, ex\ncept such of them as can be induced to\nbuy the magazine at the regular price.\nIt is not claimed that it is or will be\ncome the best magazine of its kind\npublished, only that it is the best for\nIdaho people interested in fish' and\ngame matters. Of the quality of its\ncontents, and of its possibilities for use\nfulness, readers must judge them\nselves.\nof\nof\nDon\na\nParker Takes Pen in Hand in\nDefense of His Stand on Plan\nof Apportioning Forest Funds\nGRANGEVILLE 'S PIONEER EDITOR\nSHOWS SOUTH IDAHO CRITIC\nWHY IDAHO COUNTY SHOULD\nRECEIVE MORE MONEY.\nThat Idaho county is justly entitled\nto her full share of the appoitionment\nof funds derived from the forest re\nand that the basis of such ap\nserve\nportionment should be made equally\namong the counties where such reserves\nlocated is the contention of A. F.\nare\nParker who ha\u00e4 devoted considerable\ntime and study to the subject. Follow\ning a recent speech made at the initial\nmeeting of the Idaho County Good\nRoads Association in Orangeville, when\nMr. Parker outlined his plan urging\naction by the association which would\nfavor the plan of disbursing forest re\nmoney in the county from which\nserve\nit is derived, the Idaho Daily States\nat Boise editorially attacked Mr.\nman\nParker's plan and pointed out that\nshould such become a law Ada county,\nwhich has no forest Teserve area, would\nreceive nothing. Mr. Parker has re\nplied to the Statesman 's article and his\nreply in part is here reproduced. It sets\nforth a number of interesting sidelights\nthe good roads situation and the dis\ntribution of forest reserve funds as fol\non\nlows:\nWhat Parker Has to Say.\nA glance at the conditions existing\nin Idaho county will support my con\ntention that the forest revenues should\nSTOCKMEN ORGANIZE.\nThe Idaho Cpunty Livestock Protec\ntive and Grower's Association is the\nname of the organization which was\neffected at the big meeting of the\nstockmen at the I. O. O. F. hall last\nSaturday afternoon. The objoet of the\norganization is to generally advance the\ninterests of its members and to proteet\nthem against losses,\ntheir\nA paragraph of\nThe\nby-laws\nsociation shall offer a standing reward\nof $500 to any person or persons who\nshall arrest and secure the conviction\nof any one for stealing any of the pro\ntected stock of the association.\" The\nreads:\nas\nyoung men of the county are especially\nbeing urged to get iuto the association,\nand the work will be largely one of bet\nterment oi stockgrowing conditions and\nthe general benefit of the'membership.\n\u2014Whitebird 8un.\nPLOWING ON SALMON.\nHal Brown, the well known Salmon\nriver stockman, is in town this week on\na short business visit. He recently re\nturned from the Weiser and Midvale\ncountry where he has been buying and\nshipping considerable livestock. Hal\nsays he broke into the sheep business\ndown there and found it exceedingly\nprofitable. Already there is much plow\ning and early spring farm work under\nway along the Salmon, Mr. Brown says,\nand conditions at present point to a\nfine year for that country.\nbe distributed solely in the counties\nwhere the revenues originate.\nIdaho county is the largest county\nin the state of Idaho and one of the\nlargest in the United States.\nIn this great county we have 81\nschool districts, some of them in remote\nsettlements with less than ten scholars\nw here the hire of teachers is necessarily\nhigh. We also have 48 election pre\ncincts, of which about a dozen poll less\nthan 20 votes. But no matter what the\ncost to the taxpayers of Idaho county,\nthese school districts and election pre\ncincts must be maintained. The law re\nquires that each election precinct shall\nhave three judges and two clerks of\nelection, and a constable, at $4 per day\neach. Some of these precincts are so\nfar away that even if a special messen\nger is employed they are sometimes un\nable to get ther election returns to the\ncounty seat in the ten days required by\nthe law to begin the official count.\nCompare for a moment Idaho county\nwith Ada county:\nIdaho County.\nTotal area.\nAgriculture land\nValuation\n7,222,400 acres\n147,055 acres\n.$5,020,422\nAda County.\nTotal area\nAgricultural land\nValuation\n746,800 acres\n70,564 acres\n,...$9,131,937\nThe reader can figure out the percen\ntages of agricultural land to total area,\n(Continued on Page 4.)\nPIONEER WRITES TO FRIENDS.\nLeft Prairie in 1880\u2014Was Cowboy Here\nDuring Indian War.\n.1. E. Mc.Neir, one of the pioneers who\nresided in the Orangeville country in\nthe stirring times of the Nezperee I\ndian war of 1877, has written here ask\ning for news of several persons with\nwhom he became acquainted in the\nearly days.\nnear Lincoln, Nebraska,\nhe sends his regards to his old time\nfriends, but it is a sad fact that all\nthose ho names particularly have an\nswered the call and have gone over the\nOront Divide. His letter, in part, fol\nlows:\nn*\nMr. McNeir is now living\nIn his letter\n\"Please be kind enough to tell me\nthe address of any of the children of\nSeth Jones. It has been quite a num\nber of years since 1 was there. sup\npose they have moved from the old\nhomestead just above the creek. There\nwere three girls and three boys. Should\nyou happen to see any of them please\ntell them to write. 1 was in that part\nof the country in the year of 1877 and\nleft there in the year of 1880 and went\nto Montana. Lived in Missoula for\nquite a while\n\"P. S. Regards to Bill Hill, J. H.\nRobinson, .1. M. Crooks and all the old\ntimers.\nWilliam Coram and A1 Tnlkington\nboth remember McNeir as a man who\nwas employed on the prairie as a cow\nboy. He rode for John Mack, on the\nplace now owned by Dr. W. H. Warner,\nand for George Sears, at Clearwater,\nMr. Coram states. It iH quite probable\nthat many other old pioneers will recall\nMr. McNeir, among them being James\nand Thomas Surridge, John Byrom,\nJacob and .lohn Crooks, Mrs. Charles\nBentz, ami many others. Mr. NcNeir\ngives his address as R. F. D. No. 8, Box\nbe\nly\nto\nof\nof\nall\n.1. E. McNeir.\n53.\nLARGE CLASS GRADUATES.\nThe present membership of the Glass\nof '14 includes the names of 17 well\nknown students at the local high school\nwith indications that all will be given\ndiplomas at the end of the school year.\nThe class will be one of the largest in\nnumber in the history of the school and\nthe way the several enthusiastic\nyoung men and women are putting the\nfinishing touches on their school work\nand shaping arrangements for the com\nmencement exercises and other events\nincidental to graduation indicates that\nthe class is made up of progressive boys\nand girls who may be expected to make\na record in the world after leaving\nschool on a par with the fine standard\nthey have established as students. The\nfollowing comprise the class of '14;\nPittman Atwood, Charles Branscombe,\nHugh Taylor, Clarke Rush, Roger Hill,\nArthur Horning, 8am Kennedy, Walter\nKnorr, Mary Mclntee, Rose Mclntee,\nFreda Hesterman, Martha Squibb,\nMyra Gager, Mary DeHaven, Cora\nHurley, Marietta Alexander and Helen\nGuthrie.\nHAINES IS IN RACE.\nGovernor John M. Haines is a candi\ndate for re-election. He has announced\nhis candidacy in a statement issued\nto the people of the state in which he\ndeclares that it is his intention to seek\nre-nomination and re-election on the\nrepublican ticket ns chief executive of\nIdaho and that in going before the peo\nple for indorsement ho does sq on the\nrecord lie has made, and expeets to be\njudged thereby. He is the first republi\ncan candidate and in fact the first\ncandidate of any party to cast his hat\ninto the gubernatorial ring for the Sep\ntember primaries.\nLENT BEGAN WEDNESDAY.\nThe chinch season of Lent began yes\nterday. The first day is commonly\ncalled Ash Wednesday because of a cus\ntom prevailing in the early days of\nChristianity of springling ashes on the\nhead in token of penitence and sorrow\nfor sin. The word is derived from an\nold Saxon term \"lenten,\" meaning\nspring time, alluding to the spring fast\npreparatory to the celebration of\nEaster. It also commemorates our\nLord's fasting forty days in the wild\nerness.\nBUILD ROAD AT ELK.\nWord comes out from Elk City to the\neffect that the Elk City Good Road\nBoosters have already subscribed be\ntween $4000 and $5000 to build about\nsix miles of road from Elk City toward\nGrangeville on the route of the South\nFork road. Work will start as soon as\nthe frost is out of the ground and the\nweather is settled. The Elk City and\nDixie people are enthusiastic over the\nnew road and are going to show that\nthey are in earnest about it by build\ning their share of the highway.\nGREAT ACTUM IN\nMINES ASSIED\nin\nn*\nTHIS TEAR\nIDAHO COUNTY RIPE FOR RETURN\nOF PROSPERITY THROUGHOUT\nALL MINING DISTRICTS.\nELK STRIKE STARTS BOON\nRich Find on Black Pine Re-Awakens\nWorld to Wealth of Central Idaho\nMines\u2014Revival Predicted.\nAll signs point to a milling revival in\nIdaho county, and particularly in the\nElk City-Orogrando districts, if the de\nvelopment* of the past few weeks may\nbe taken ns a criterion and it is the\njudgment of many level-headed and\nconservative citizens, both mining men\nand business men, that the time is ripe\nfor the return of the days of mining\nactivity which brought Jduho county\ninto the limelight so effectively a few\nyears ago.\nWhile there has been no great stride\nforward in the industry during tho past\nfour years, that is, strides marked by\nreports of fabulously rich strikes,\nstories (hat extensive and costly mining\noperations would be continued broad\ncast throughout the mining districts\nreports that the average citizen iB al\nways inclined to discredit\u2014it is never\nthe less a salient and all-apparent fact\nthat the development of the mines in\nIdaho county has been going on steadi\nly and surely; all over the county there\nlias been no let up. The rule has been\nto peg away despite lack of transpor\ntation and adequate mining machinery\nand equipment. It is true that the\nBuster, one of the most famous proper\nties in the county, has suspended opera\ntions, but in the face of this, the camp\nof Elk City has been the scene of a\nsteady development of properties, many\nof which already promise to eclipse the\nBlister in due time. It is apparent that\nall mines must pass through a certain\nstage of development before they be\ncome real producers. This fact, it is\nargued, is particularly true of the\nquartz properties in the Elk City, Buf\nfalo Hump, Ten Mile, OroGrande, and\nother districts of the county. The past\nfew vearB have witnessed a program of\nquiet but steady and certain work on\ncountless mines throughout this section.\nThe work has gone on for the most part\nwithout clamor or comment; mining\ntools have been worn, repaired or re\nplenished rather than press agents'\npencils; men who by their work in the\nhills have come to know that the yel\nlow metal is deposited there have\ndirected most of the work\u2014in many\ncases they have been the toilers with\nthe (lick and the shovel and the wheel\nbarrow\u2014they have attested to their\nfaith in the district by actual work, by\nsticking to the camp after many of the\npessimistic residenters had given up.\nThat the patient efforts of those men\nwho have long proclaimed the wealth of\nIdaho county's mines are about to be\nrewarded seems undeniable at this time.\nThe news of the recent strike on the\nBlack l'ine near Elk City, together with\nthe announcement that the Colonel Sel\nlers at that place is working night and\nday shifts and the further realization\nthat countless properties in the hills\nnearby have passed through the devel\nopment stages and are ready to become\nsteady producers gives foundation for\nthe belief that a new era in Idaho\ncounty mining is at hand.\nThompson's Views.\nCharles hompson, one of the best\nknown mining men in the county, and\nformerly deputy sheriff, came out from\nElk City the last of the week and while\nhe did not get to visit the Black Pine\nmine he saw some of the ore from the\nproperty which he pronounces excep\ntionally good. \"From what I was told\nby responsible parties at Elk City,\nsaid Mr. Thompson yesterday;\nmen at work on the Black Pine have\nrun tho r drift in about 25 feet already\nand all the way it is in splendid ore.\nThe lend was some two feet wide when\nit was first tapped but in the 25 feet\nalready traversed it has broadened to a\ntotal width of five and a half feet,\nwith 22 inches or ore on the hanging\nwall. It is said to be a hematite grade\nof ore. The miners on the property are\nContinued on page 4.)\nin\nhe\nthe\nof\nthe\nbe\nhat\ncus\nof\nthe\nan\nfast\nof\nour\nthe\nbe\nas\nthe\nand\nthe\nthat\n\nthe\ni","height":"20520","width":"13944"}}
